1. Introduction

1.1 Purpose:

The purpose of this project is to study and analyze the credit card dataset using different data analysis techniques and to come up with a possible best model that can predict the credit limit based on the predictors.

During the study, we will use the following data analysis techniques on the dataset

  1. Data cleaning as necessary to address observations with missing or extreme values.
  2. Multiple linear regression
  3. ANOVA
  4. Dummy variables
  5. Interaction
  6. Residual diagnostics
  7. Outlier diagnostics
  8. Transformations
  9. Polynomial regression
  10. Stepwise model selection
  11. Variable selection criteria

1.2 About the data:

The dataset contains information of credit card customers. The details are broadly classified into

  • Information about the customers wrt their Age, Education, Martial Status and Family etc.
  • Their credit card usage patterns like Total transactions, Average utilization ratio, Total revolving balances etc.
  • Banks decision on the Credit limit.

1.3 Source:

https://www.kaggle.com/sakshigoyal7/credit-card-customers

1.4 Description of the data file:

This dataset consists of details of 10,128 customer records mentioning their age, salary, marital_status, credit card limit, credit card category, etc. There are totally 23 variables (features). Some of the important variables are

Variable Description
CLIENTNUM Unique identifier for the customer holding the account
Attrition_Flag Internal event (customer activity) variable - if the account is closed then 1 else 0
Customer_Age Demographic variable - Customer’s Age in Years
Gender Demographic variable - M=Male, F=Female
Dependent_count Demographic variable - Number of dependents
Education_Level Demographic variable - Educational Qualification of the account holder (example: high school, college graduate, etc.)
Marital_Status Demographic variable - Married, Single, Divorced, Unknown
Income_Category Demographic variable - Annual Income Category of the account holder (< $40K, $40K - 60K, $60K - $80K, $80K-$120K, > $120K, Unknown)
Card_Category Product Variable - Type of Card (Blue, Silver, Gold, Platinum)
Months_on_book Period of relationship with bank
Total_Relationship_Count Total no. of products held by the customer
Months_Inactive_12_mon No. of months inactive in the last 12 months
Contacts_Count_12_mon No. of Contacts in the last 12 months
Credit_Limit Credit Limit on the Credit Card
Total_Revolving_Bal Total Revolving Balance on the Credit Card
Avg_Open_To_Buy Open to Buy Credit Line (Average of last 12 months)
Total_Amt_Chng_Q4_Q1 Change in Transaction Amount (Q4 over Q1)
Total_Trans_Amt Total Transaction Amount (Last 12 months)
Total_Trans_Ct Total Transaction Count (Last 12 months)
Total_Ct_Chng_Q4_Q1 Change in Transaction Count (Q4 over Q1)
Avg_Utilization_Ratio Average Card Utilization Ratio

2.1 Library loading & Utility Methods:

options(scipen=1, digits=2)
library(lmtest)
library(faraway)
#install.packages("gdata")
library(gdata)

#install.packages("corrplot")
library(corrplot)

get_rmse = function(model) {
  sqrt(mean(resid(model) ^ 2))
}

calc_loocv_rmse = function(model) {
  sqrt(mean((resid(model) / (1 - hatvalues(model))) ^ 2))
}

2.5 Variable Selection & Model Building:

AIC Forward:

creditcard_data_model_start = lm(Credit_Limit ~ 1,data = creditcard_data)
creditcard_data_model_aic = step(creditcard_data_model_start, scope = Credit_Limit ~  Customer_Age + Gender + Dependent_count + Education_Level + Marital_Status + Income_Category + Months_on_book + Total_Relationship_Count + Months_Inactive_12_mon + Contacts_Count_12_mon + Total_Revolving_Bal + Total_Amt_Chng_Q4_Q1 + Total_Trans_Amt + Total_Trans_Ct + Total_Ct_Chng_Q4_Q1 + Avg_Utilization_Ratio, direction ="forward", trace = FALSE)

aic_forward_adjrsquared = summary(creditcard_data_model_aic)$adj.r.squared
aic_forward_rmse = get_rmse(creditcard_data_model_aic)
aic_forward_loocv_rmse = calc_loocv_rmse(creditcard_data_model_aic)
aic_forward_no_params = length(as.data.frame(coef(creditcard_data_model_aic))[ ,1]) - 1
aic_forward_vif_gt5 = sum(vif(creditcard_data_model_aic) > 5)

AIC Backward:

creditcard_data_model_aic_backward_start = lm(Credit_Limit ~ Customer_Age + Gender + Dependent_count + Education_Level + Marital_Status + Income_Category + Months_on_book + Total_Relationship_Count + Months_Inactive_12_mon + Contacts_Count_12_mon + Total_Revolving_Bal + Total_Amt_Chng_Q4_Q1 + Total_Trans_Amt + Total_Trans_Ct + Total_Ct_Chng_Q4_Q1 + Avg_Utilization_Ratio, data = creditcard_data)
creditcard_data_model_aic_backward = step(creditcard_data_model_aic_backward_start, trace = FALSE)

aic_backward_adjrsquared = summary(creditcard_data_model_aic_backward)$adj.r.squared
aic_backward_rmse = get_rmse(creditcard_data_model_aic_backward)
aic_backward_loocv_rmse = calc_loocv_rmse(creditcard_data_model_aic_backward)
aic_backward_no_params = length(as.data.frame(coef(creditcard_data_model_aic_backward))[ ,1]) - 1
aic_backward_vif_gt5 = sum(vif(creditcard_data_model_aic) > 5)

BIC Forward:

creditcard_data_model_start = lm(Credit_Limit ~ 1, data = creditcard_data)
creditcard_data_model_bic = step(creditcard_data_model_start, scope = Credit_Limit ~  Customer_Age + Gender + Dependent_count + Education_Level + Marital_Status + Income_Category + Months_on_book + Total_Relationship_Count + Months_Inactive_12_mon + Contacts_Count_12_mon + Total_Revolving_Bal + Total_Amt_Chng_Q4_Q1 + Total_Trans_Amt + Total_Trans_Ct + Total_Ct_Chng_Q4_Q1 + Avg_Utilization_Ratio , direction ="forward", trace = FALSE, k = log(nrow(creditcard_data)))

bic_forward_adjrsquared = summary(creditcard_data_model_bic)$adj.r.squared
bic_forward_rmse = get_rmse(creditcard_data_model_bic)
bic_forward_loocv_rmse = calc_loocv_rmse(creditcard_data_model_bic)
bic_forward_no_params = length(as.data.frame(coef(creditcard_data_model_bic))[ ,1]) - 1
bic_forward_vif_gt5 = sum(vif(creditcard_data_model_bic) > 5)

BIC Backward:

creditcard_data_model_bic_backward_start = lm(Credit_Limit ~ Customer_Age + Gender + Dependent_count + Education_Level + Marital_Status + Income_Category + Months_on_book + Total_Relationship_Count + Months_Inactive_12_mon + Contacts_Count_12_mon + Total_Revolving_Bal + Total_Amt_Chng_Q4_Q1 + Total_Trans_Amt + Total_Trans_Ct + Total_Ct_Chng_Q4_Q1 + Avg_Utilization_Ratio, data = creditcard_data)
creditcard_data_model_bic_backward = step(creditcard_data_model_bic_backward_start, trace = FALSE,  k = log(nrow(creditcard_data)))

bic_backward_adjrsquared = summary(creditcard_data_model_bic_backward)$adj.r.squared 
bic_backward_rmse = get_rmse(creditcard_data_model_bic_backward)
bic_backward_loocv_rmse = calc_loocv_rmse(creditcard_data_model_bic_backward)
bic_backward_no_params = length(as.data.frame(coef(creditcard_data_model_bic_backward))[ ,1]) - 1
bic_backward_vif_gt5 = sum(vif(creditcard_data_model_bic_backward) > 5)

BIC Both:

creditcard_data_model_both_start = lm(Credit_Limit ~ 1,data = creditcard_data)
creditcard_data_model_bic_both = step(creditcard_data_model_both_start, scope = Credit_Limit ~  Customer_Age + Gender + Dependent_count + Education_Level + Marital_Status + Income_Category + Months_on_book + Total_Relationship_Count + Months_Inactive_12_mon + Contacts_Count_12_mon + Total_Revolving_Bal + Total_Amt_Chng_Q4_Q1 + Total_Trans_Amt + Total_Trans_Ct + Total_Ct_Chng_Q4_Q1 + Avg_Utilization_Ratio, trace = FALSE, direction = "both",  k = log(nrow(creditcard_data)))

bic_both_adjrsquared = summary(creditcard_data_model_bic_both)$adj.r.squared 
bic_both_rmse = get_rmse(creditcard_data_model_bic_both) 
bic_both_loocv_rmse = calc_loocv_rmse(creditcard_data_model_bic_both)
bic_both_no_params = length(as.data.frame(coef(creditcard_data_model_bic_both))[ ,1]) - 1
bic_both_vif_gt5 = sum(vif(creditcard_data_model_bic_both) > 5)

3.5 Test and Train

We tried to test and train the model to predict and find the RMSE between train and test splits. Following are the results.

set.seed(22)
creditcard_data_sample_trn_idx = sample(1:nrow(creditcard_data), 5000) # randomly chosen observations for training
auto_trn = creditcard_data[creditcard_data_sample_trn_idx, ]
auto_tst = creditcard_data[-creditcard_data_sample_trn_idx, ]

final_selected_model_train = lm(log(Credit_Limit) ~ Income_Category + Avg_Utilization_Ratio + Total_Revolving_Bal + Total_Trans_Amt + Marital_Status + Dependent_count +  Total_Trans_Amt:Avg_Utilization_Ratio + Income_Category:Avg_Utilization_Ratio + Income_Category:Total_Revolving_Bal + Dependent_count:Marital_Status + I(Avg_Utilization_Ratio ^ 2), data= auto_trn)

rmse  = function(actual, predicted) {
  sqrt(mean((actual - predicted) ^ 2))
}

# calculate all train errors
train_error = c(
  rmse(auto_trn$Credit_Limit, exp(predict(final_selected_model_train, auto_trn)))
)

# calculate all test errors
test_error = c(
  rmse(auto_tst$Credit_Limit, exp(predict(final_selected_model_train, auto_tst))) 
)

auto_models = c("`Final Selected Model`")
auto_results = data.frame(auto_models, train_error, test_error)
colnames(auto_results) = c("Model", "Train RMSE", "Test RMSE")
knitr::kable(auto_results, "simple")
Model Train RMSE Test RMSE
Final Selected Model 4918 4838

From the results, we can see that both test and train RMSE are similar which indicates the model is good and well fitted.

4. Discussion

Clicking on the below header anchors will take to corresponding sections in the method area to see the code and output.

  • About the data

    • The dataset contains around 10128 rows and 23 variables as noted here

    • We observed the following three variables will not contribute to the model and prediction. Hence, while reading the data, we removed those variables.

      “CLIENTNUM”,
      “Naive_Bayes_Classifier_Attrition_Flag_Card_Category_Contacts_Count_12_mon_Dependent_count_Education_Level_Months_Inactive_12_mon_1”,
      “Naive_Bayes_Classifier_Attrition_Flag_Card_Category_Contacts_Count_12_mon_Dependent_count_Education_Level_Months_Inactive_12_mon_2”

  • Data Cleaning

    • The dataset also had many “Unknown” values in several columns of several rows. As part of data cleaning effort, We removed those rows which had any column values having “Unknown” using the following technique below,

      • First, Use the unknownToNA method from gdata package to convert the unknown values to NA.
      • Then use na.omit method to remove those rows.

  • Dummy / Factor Variables

    • We also noticed few factor variables in our dataset. The factor variables we observed are Attrition_Flag, Gender, Education_Level, Maritial_Status, Income_Category, Card_Category. We changed them to factor variables in the dataset using as.factor method.


  • Full Additive Model

    • We started fitting with a full additive model with all the predictors except the 3 variables which we observed will not contribute to the model. We noticed F-Statistic value is not significant for this additive model regression.

    • Since the f-statistic was very low for the additive model, we decided to proceed with finding the best model using variable selection and other model building techniques (AIC, BIC etc).


  • Variable Selection & Model Building

    • Based on the above table results, BIC seems to be performing better WRT to Adjusted R-Squared and Number of predictors in the model. Hence we choose the model provided by BIC backward. We also noticed the F-statistic value improved significantly for the model provided by BIC backwards.


  • Interaction Model

    • In order to improve the LOOCV-RMSE and Adjusted R-Squared, we started with all two way interactions.

    • Based on the results and observations, we choose the interactions that are Significant and logical to come up with the following best interaction model. We also notice a decent adjusted R2 and RMSE values for the interaction model.

    • To test the significance of interaction model, we performed the following anova test. Since the p-value of anova test is 2.2e-16, we reject the null hypothesis and the interaction model is preferred.


  • Polynomial Terms

    • From the results, because ‘Avg_Utilization_Ratio’ was a main predictor that interacted with most of the other predictors, we added a second degree polynomial term to improve the adjusted r squared and RMSE.

    • To test the significance of interaction model, we performed the following anova test. Since the p-value of anova test is 2.2e-16, we reject the null hypothesis and the polynomial model is preferred.


  • Transformations

    • To further improve the r-squared and RMSE, we transformed the response variable by adding log to it.


  • Model Assumptions & Model Diagnostics Tests

    • Fitted vs Residuals & Normal Q-Q plots give below
    • Even with the best model, normality and equal variance assumption seems to be violated. This can be confirmed from BP Test and Shapiro tests as well. We believe this is due to the nature of the data.


  • Best Model:

    • From all the analysis and transformations, we were able to arrive at the following best model
    • credit_card_final_model = lm(log(Credit_Limit) ~ Income_Category + Avg_Utilization_Ratio + Total_Revolving_Bal + Total_Trans_Amt + Marital_Status + Dependent_count + Total_Trans_Amt:Avg_Utilization_Ratio + Income_Category:Avg_Utilization_Ratio + Income_Category:Total_Revolving_Bal + Dependent_count:Marital_Status + I(Avg_Utilization_Ratio ^ 2), data= creditcard_data)
